description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/transport/kiss_transport.c
Lines: 84-148

kiss_decode_byte() checks for NULL ctx and returns -EINVAL (lines 86-88), but then the function is called from kiss_rx_thread_fn (line 393) and kiss_transport_test_inject_rx (line 672) where ctx is always valid.

The issue is that the NULL check provides a false sense of safety. If the context were actually NULL, returning -EINVAL is correct, but the callers in this file never check for this error - they only check for ret == 1 (frame complete) or ret < 0 (error).

In kiss_rx_thread_fn:
    int ret = kiss_decode_byte(&ctx->rx_ctx, buf[i]);
    if (ret == 1) { ... }
    else if (ret < 0) { ... }

If ctx were NULL, -EINVAL would be treated as a frame error, but the LOG_WRN at line 120/141 would have already dereferenced ctx->in_frame, causing a crash before returning.

Fix: The NULL check at line 86-88 is dead code since all callers pass valid context. Either remove it (simpler) or make the function truly NULL-safe by checking ctx before any dereference.
